A '''techno-thriller''' (also known as '''technothrillers''') is a hybrid genre drawing from [[science fiction]], [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]s, [[spy fiction]], [[action (fiction)|action]], and [[War novel|war novels]]. They include a disproportionate amount (relative to other genres) of technical details on their subject matter (typically military technology); only [[hard science fiction]] tends towards a comparable level of supporting detail on the technical side. The inner workings of technology and the mechanics of various disciplines ([[espionage]], [[martial arts]], [[politics]]) are thoroughly explored, and the plot often turns on the particulars of that exploration.

== History ==
One of the earliest techno-thrillers is thought to be ''[[The Satan Bug (novel)|The Satan Bug]]'' (1962) by [[Alistair MacLean]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gullcottageonline.com/Buried_Treas.html|title=Alistair MacLean's THE SATAN BUG: Birth of the Techno-Thriller - by CEJ|work=gullcottageonline}}</ref> 
[[Michael Crichton]] and [[Tom Clancy]] are considered to be the fathers of the "modern techno-thriller";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-04-11/features/9302050353_1_tom-clancy-clancy-novel-fiction|title=Father Of Our Country? Tom Clancy Created The Techno-thriller, And He Did It With A Pro-american Mindset.|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel}}</ref> Crichton's book ''[[The Andromeda Strain]]'' and Clancy's book ''[[The Hunt for Red October]]'' set out the type example which defined the genre, although many authors had been writing similar material earlier, such as [[Craig Thomas (author)|Craig Thomas]], whom [[BBC News]] also credits as an early innovator.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-east-wales-13012763|title=Techno thriller writer Craig Thomas dies|author=<!-- Staff -->|work=[[BBC News]]|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>

== Style ==
Techno-thrillers focus strongly on details, especially on the technology, which is frequently of military origin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-10-02/entertainment/bs-md-clancy-appreciation-20131002_1_tom-clancy-cold-war-red-october|title=Clancy invented 'techno-thriller,' reflected Cold War fears|last=Kaltenbach|first=Chris|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/10/02/tom-clancy-appreciation/2908305/|title=Appreciation: Tom Clancy mastered the techno-thriller|last=Minzesheimer|first=Bob|work=[[USA Today]]|date=3 October 2013|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Techno-thrillers tend to have a broad scope in the narrative, and can often be regarded as contemporary speculative fiction; world wars are a common topic. Techno-thrillers often overlap, as far as the genre goes, with near-future science fiction, [[War_novel|military fiction]], and [[Spy_fiction|espionage fiction]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.writersdigest.com/writing-articles/by-writing-genre/varieties-of-the-technothriller-genre|title=Crypto, Sci-Fi, Soldiers, Spies (and Disasters): 5 Varieties Within the Technothriller Genre|last=Boush|first=Sam|work=[[Writer's Digest]]|date=19 July 2018|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> To the extent that technology is now a dominant aspect of modern global culture, most modern thrillers are "techno-thrillers", and the genre is somewhat diffuse. Techno-thrillers blur smoothly into the category of [[hard science fiction]]; the defining characteristics of techno-thriller are an emphasis on real-world or plausible near-future technology. There is often a focus on military or military-political action. Techno-thrillers also overlap with [[conspiracy fiction]] and [[apocalyptic fiction]].

