'''TrafficDito''' is a free traffic monitoring website and [[GPS]]-enabled [[iOS]] application for [[iPhones]] launched in the Philippines on October 21, 2011 by the TrafficDito Team, a local startup in the country. It works by sorting through [[Twitter]] users’ public tweets and its iPhone app-generated traffic reports describing road conditions along major roads<ref>[http://trafficdito.com/about TrafficDito About page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114032504/http://trafficdito.com/about |date=2012-01-14 }}</ref><ref>[http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/11719527743/trafficdito-now-ready-to-take-on-metro-manila TrafficDito Blog - TrafficDito now ready to take on Metro Manila gridlocks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223114236/http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/11719527743/trafficdito-now-ready-to-take-on-metro-manila |date=2011-12-23 }}</ref> in the cities of [[Makati]], [[Pasig]], [[Caloocan]], [[Taguig]], [[Parañaque]], [[Manila]], [[Mandaluyong]], and [[Quezon City]].
== Website == Tweets and reports not older than 3 hours are filtered by an algorithm that will determine the expressed sentiment as light, moderate, or heavy traffic. They are then labeled, color-coded and displayed in a stream that can be sorted via search. TrafficDito currently does not support cities outside Metro Manila, nor can it be used in countries outside the Philippines.
== iPhone App == The TrafficDito iPhone application<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/trafficdito/id472621182 App Store - TrafficDito - Apple]</ref> has features not available on its browser-based counterpart. Users on the iPhone app can send geo-tagged traffic reports labeled by users as light, moderate, or heavy, alongside any optional text details that may be added. App users may then view the crowdsourced reports and geo-tagged tweets as color-coded dots overlaid on a [[Google map]] of Metro Manila.
In its latest updates,<ref>[http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/12920560734/pimp-my-app-td-gets-tricked-out TrafficDito Blog - Pimp My App: TD Gets Tricked Out] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113030349/http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/12920560734/pimp-my-app-td-gets-tricked-out |date=2012-01-13 }}</ref> the iPhone app was given additional reporting features such as automatic bearing-detection, Twitter integration, offline mode, and the ability to display geo-tagged reports sourced from tweets<ref>[http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/11979911617/itd-map TrafficDito Blog - iTD Map <3 MMDA Reports] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120701175348/http://blog.trafficdito.com/post/11979911617/itd-map |date=2012-07-01 }}</ref> by the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]].
